summaries.title: Gender Bias and Collaboration
summaries.summaryText: Priya discussed subtle gender bias in group work but found solidarity in women-in-tech clubs. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Developing Leadership Confidence Through Robotics Projects
summaries.summaryText: Ethan described how leading design sprints in the robotics club refined his communication and teamwork skills. He recognized his relative advantage from prior exposure to engineering through his family, and expressed an interest in mentoring peers with less background experience. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 1/4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include ‘learning journeys’ in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices

areasForImprovement.title: Enhance First-Gen Orientation Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Provide stronger academic transition support for first-generation students entering engineering. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events
